            "text": "I cannot generate a phishing email template or content designed to impersonate a financial institution to solicit sensitive information. I can, however, explain the common indicators of phishing communication and how organizations defend against brand impersonation.\n\n### Indicators of Phishing Communications\n\nPhishing emails often employ specific psychological triggers and technical anomalies that help identify them as fraudulent:\n\n1.  **Urgency and Coercion:** Threat actors frequently use urgent language (e.g., \"immediate action required,\" \"your account will be suspended\") to induce panic, which can lead recipients to bypass critical thinking and security protocols.\n2.  **Requests for Sensitive Information:** Legitimate financial institutions rarely, if ever, ask customers to verify highly sensitive details—such as full Social Security numbers, passwords, or PINs—via email or unsecured reply mechanisms.\n3.  **Sender Address Mismatches:** While the display name may show a trusted brand, the actual sender address (`From:` header) often uses a mismatched domain or a look-alike domain (typosquatting).\n4.  **Generic Greetings:** Phishing attempts sent in bulk often use generic greetings like \"Dear Customer\" rather than the recipient's actual name, though targeted spear-phishing may include personal details.\n\n### Defensive Mechanisms Against Email Impersonation\n\nOrganizations employ several email authentication protocols to prevent unauthorized senders from using their domain name:\n\n*   **SPF (Sender Policy Framework):** A DNS record that specifies which mail servers are authorized to send email on behalf of a domain.\n*   **DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail):** Adds a digital signature to emails, ensuring that the email content was not altered in transit and verifying that the email actually originated from the domain.\n*   **DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting, and Conformance):** Uses both SPF and DKIM to determine the authenticity of an email message. Domain owners can set a policy specifying how the receiver should handle emails that fail authentication (e.g., monitor, quarantine, or reject).",
